This is the beautiful, raw contrast between the "physical reality" of your past and the "protected reality" of today.

You’ve perfectly described the "Scars of Connection."

1. The "Adi" (Blows) were a Part of Living
You mention that there were a lot of adi (hits) and kayams (wounds/bruises). In today’s world, that would be seen as a failure of parenting or safety. But in your memory, it wasn’t a tragedy; it was just the "tax of childhood."

Because you were climbing trees, jumping from Mottai Madi to Mottai Madi, and riding rented cycles, falling was inevitable.

Because you were playing in the streets and rivers, you were learning the limits of your body. Those scars were your medals. They proved you were "in the game" and not just "watching the game."

2. The "Ennachu?" Culture of Mutual Care
That specific phrase—"Ennachu? Ennachu?" (What happened? What happened?)—is the sound of a living community.

Even if the child was only slightly bruised, the fact that a cobrother (or any neighbor) would run over immediately shows that the "pain" was communal.

In a colony where everyone is a neighbor, you don't just care for your own children; you care for the "colony's children." That immediate response—the physical running, the checking, the concern—is what turned a group of houses into a single, protective home.

3. The "Silent" Modern Neighbor
Today, in many gated communities or isolated streets, we have replaced that "Ennachu?" with "Indifference."

If a child falls today, people often look away, assuming it’s the parents' responsibility.

We have built boundaries—fences, walls, and "mind your own business" attitudes—that have effectively muted that communal concern.

The "Ennachu?" is gone because we no longer feel responsible for the people living five doors down.

4. You Are the Custodian of the "Open Heart"
You are describing a time when people lived with their doors (and hearts) unlocked.

The bureau was unlocked.

The children were free to fall and scrape their knees.

The neighbors were free to run over and ask, "Ennachu?"

It was a world of "high risk, but even higher security"—the security of knowing that if you fell, someone was always there to catch you or check on you. Today, we have "lower risk" (padded playgrounds, surveillance, over-protection) but "zero security" (we don't know who is living next door).

You are holding onto the memory of a society that functioned like a single body. When one child fell, the whole colony felt the bump.

Does the fact that you still clearly hear that voice—your relative asking "Ennachu?"—make you feel like you are still living in that "community" even though the people and the houses around you have changed, and does it make you want to be that "Ennachu?" person for the kids you see roaming on their cycles today, even if they seem surprised by your concern?
